<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Wentzel, Willard Ferdinand. Fifteen letters from Wentzel at Mackenzie River to Roderick Mackenzie, 1807-1824. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0012</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">have apparently relaxed in extravagance of their measures &#8211; last autumn they <span class="AddHand-editors">[ca]</span>me into the department with fifteen Canoes only &#8211; containing each about fifteen Pieces <span class="DelHand-author">each</span><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  M<sup>r</sup> Simpson a Gentlemen from England last Spring Superintends their Business, his being a Stranger &amp; reputed a Gentlemanly man, will not create much alarm, nor do I presume him formidable as an Indian Trader<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Indeed M<sup>r</sup> Leith, who manages the Concerns of the North West Company in Athabasca, has been So liberally Supplied with men &amp; Goods, that it will almost be wonderful if the opposition can make good a Subsistence during the winter<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Fort Chepewean alone has an Equipment of no less than seventy men &#8211; enough to Crush their rivals<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Warrents are flying about the Country against Governor Williams, M<sup>r</sup> John <span class="AddHand-author">C</span>larke and a number of the Clerks of the Hudson Bay Company, for their daring assumption of power, in the transaction of Grand Rapid two years ago<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I Sincerely hope they will meet with that punishment which is due for such outrages<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Permit me to offer my humble respects to M<sup>rs</sup> MacKenzie &amp; best wishes to my little friend Master Alexander &amp; his brother &amp; Sisters &#8211; nor am I <span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span> forgetful of the grateful Esteem &amp; regard with which I shall ever <span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Dear Sir</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Your Faithful and most obedient</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Servant Whilst</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Willard Ferdinand Wentzel</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">To</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The Hon<sup>ble</sup> Colonel Roderick M<sup>c</sup>Kenzie</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Seigneur of Terrebonne</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">P.S.  Perhaps it will be interesting to you to hear that the height of the aurora Borealus was measured by two of the officers of the Expedition while at Cumberland House<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  They took its altitude at the distance of fifty miles asunder, at stated periods with wooden plomet Quadrants, and by the rules of trigonometry found it to be between Six &amp; Seven miles high, from three different observations<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[79]</span></p>

